1️⃣ Configuration Differences
Common issues:
Missing or incorrect environment variables
Different feature flags
Different limits (timeouts, memory, CPU)
Secrets not configured the same way
Hard‑coded values in dev

Example:
Dev: timeout = 60s ✅
Prod: timeout = 5s ❌ → requests fail

💡 Insight
Configuration is code — when unmanaged, it breaks production.


2️⃣ Environment Parity Problems (Very Common)
Dev ≠ Prod in:
Infrastructure size
Networking
Security policies
Load balancers
Firewalls / NAT / proxies

Example:
Dev uses localhost DB
Prod uses remote DB with latency
App wasn’t designed for latency → fails

💡 Key truth
Code that works without network latency often fails when real latency appears.


3️⃣ Data Differences (Huge Cause of Prod Failures)
Dev:
Small datasets
Clean data
Rare edge cases

Prod:
Large datasets
Corrupt / unexpected data
Edge cases everywhere

Example:
Query works on 100 rows
Times out on 10 million rows

💡 DevOps truth
Production data is always more hostile than test data.


4️⃣ Load & Concurrency (Dev Is Too Quiet)
Dev:
Single user
No contention
No concurrency stress

Prod:
Thousands of concurrent users
Race conditions
Lock contention
Connection pool exhaustion

Example:
App works for 1 user
Fails when 100 users hit it at once

💡 Key insight
Most bugs only appear under load.


5️⃣ External Dependencies Behave Differently
Dev:
Mocked services
No failures
Infinite retries

Prod:
Real services
Rate limits
Timeouts
Partial failures

Example:
API never fails in dev
Intermittent failures in prod → cascade

💡 System design lesson
Production dependencies will fail — dev ones usually don’t.


6️⃣ Security & Permissions (Often Ignored)
Dev:
Admin access
Open permissions
No IAM restrictions

Prod:
Least privilege
Tight security
Network ACLs

Example:
Dev app can access everything
Prod app gets “permission denied”

💡 DevOps reality
Security is lenient in dev, strict in prod — and that breaks code.


✅ Final Senior‑Level Answer (Interview‑Ready)
If asked in an interview, this is the perfect answer:
“Works in dev but fails in prod” happens because dev and prod environments differ in configuration, data volume, traffic patterns, security restrictions, network latency, and dependency behavior. 
These differences expose assumptions in the code and system design that were never tested in development.
